  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The maiden pleased him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally, \"was good in his eyes,\" the same expression as that which occurs in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 1:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". And she obtained kindness of him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is a phrase peculiar to the Book of Esther, and a favourite one with the author (see vers. 15, 17; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is better translated \"she obtained favour\" (as in all the other places where it occurs) than \"she obtained kindness,\" though the latter translation is more literal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". Her things for purification.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " See ver. 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". With such things as belonged to her",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally, as in the margin, \"with her portions\" - by which is probably meant her daily allowance of food. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And seven maidens",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, \"and her seven maidens.\" It is implied that each virgin had seven female attendants assigned to her. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Meet to be given her",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was in this point that the \"favour\" or \"kindness of Hegel was shown. He selected for her use the most suitable of the attendants. Esther 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When, then, the king's commandment and decree was heard, i.e., proclaimed throughout the kingdom, and many maidens gathered together in Susa, Esther also was received into the royal harem, under the keeping of Hegai. The maiden pleased him and won his favour (חסד נשׂא, to bear away love, i.e., to obtain favour, synonymous with חן נשׂא, ",
        "children": []
      },
